1
00:00:04,590 --> 00:00:07,610
If you have a quantitative variable,

2
00:00:07,610 --> 00:00:11,830
then your univariate plot of choice will probably be the histogram.

3
00:00:11,830 --> 00:00:18,150
Similar to a bar chart you have feature values on the x-axis and counts on the y-axis.

4
00:00:18,150 --> 00:00:21,390
However, due to the numeric nature of the data,

5
00:00:21,390 --> 00:00:23,860
bars in a histogram do not indicate counts on

6
00:00:23,860 --> 00:00:27,940
single values but instead counts on value ranges.

7
00:00:27,940 --> 00:00:33,310
In this histogram, we have plotted 30 values with bins of size three.

8
00:00:33,310 --> 00:00:36,050
The first bin on the left counts two data

9
00:00:36,050 --> 00:00:38,705
points that take a value between zero and three,

10
00:00:38,705 --> 00:00:43,745
the second bin counts four points between three and six and so on.

11
00:00:43,745 --> 00:00:49,430
Normally, bins include values on their left end and exclude values on their right end.

12
00:00:49,430 --> 00:00:54,330
So the datapoint with value 6.0 will go into the bin on its right.

13
00:00:54,330 --> 00:00:59,290
The size of the bins can have a major effect on how you interpret the data.

14
00:00:59,290 --> 00:01:01,540
If your bin size is too large,

15
00:01:01,540 --> 00:01:06,550
then you may end up losing a lot of information about the overall distribution of data.

16
00:01:06,550 --> 00:01:10,210
On the opposite side, a too small bin size can

17
00:01:10,210 --> 00:01:14,115
introduce noise that can distract from the main trends in your data.

18
00:01:14,115 --> 00:01:16,200
When creating a histogram,

19
00:01:16,200 --> 00:01:19,820
it's a good idea to play around with different settings for the bin sizes and

20
00:01:19,820 --> 00:01:24,400
boundary points to achieve a good understanding of the plotted variable.

